title: Copy of Eligibility Layer and Shadow Test - Q1 2026

textRun.content: Rehana Ashraf, Stephen Gershman, Sam Singh, Shashank Menon

Partners cannot reliably find jobs that match their machines, capabilities, and certifications on Xometry, making it harder for them to build a successful and financially healthy business. Xometry already has these jobs, but many partners simply are not being shown the work they are fully qualified to complete, leaving revenue on the table for both the partner and the marketplace.

Consolidate and organize all eligibility rules, data inputs, and decision pathways into a single, consistent framework that accurately determines which partners should see which jobs. This ensures that partners are shown relevant work that matches their capabilities, which increases their opportunity to earn income and build a reliable business on Xometry.
Validate Hypothesis: Stripping down the criteria by which Job Offers are filtered for partners to the bare minimum will result in more job offers being shown to more partners
Without running this test, we dont know what the impact this bare-minimal layer would have on job offers per partner or partners per job.
We wont have a baseline to test future limiting criteria (targeting layer or ranking) against.
We can validate that all partners will only get access to jobs they can fulfill when passed through the new eligibility layer
Number of available Job Offers per partner will increase when passed through the new eligibility layer vs the current capable partner API
Number of partners per Job Offers will increase when passed through the new eligibility layer vs the current capable partner API
Partner teams have access to reporting and traceability tools and feel confident that they understand the functionality of the eligibility layer.
Partner teams become evangelists of the three layer cake and engage actively in defining the next rounds of iteration.

Eligibility logic today is fragmented across code paths, manual checks, and legacy spreadsheets. There is no single source of truth or ability to simulate rule changes, and performance varies heavily by capability coverage. Q3 2025 analysis shows that only 53% of approved CNC partners are eligible for the average domestic single part job and that low coverage directly correlates with lower acceptance and margin. Repeat work rules, certifications, finishes, inspections, and overrides are the most common sources of restriction.

In scope for the following channels
Partners will see this if they are do the following types of jobs
As a partner I SHALL only be able to access jobs on the job board that I can execute so that Im not mistakenly accepting jobs that Ill fail in and/or have to cancel later.
(The sub-bullets below are the definition of the Eligibility Layer referenced throughout this document)
I SHALL NOT get access to jobs that fall outside of the capabilities I can execute in my shop
I SHALL NOT get access to jobs that require materials I cannot support (Material)
I SHALL NOT get access to jobs that require additive materials I cannot support
I SHALL NOT get access to jobs that require processes that I cannot support (Process)
I SHALL NOT get access to jobs that require subprocesses that I cannot support
I SHALL NOT get access to jobs that require inspections I cannot complete (Inspections)
I SHALL NOT get access to jobs that require quality inspections I cannot complete
I SHALL NOT get access to jobs that I cannot legally fulfill
I SHALL NOT get access to jobs that are legally required to be produced in a location that does not match my own (Production Location)
I SHALL NOT get access to jobs that legally require material certifications I do not have (Material Certification)
I SHALL NOT get access to jobs that legally require me to have certifications I do not have. (Partner Certification)
I SHALL NOT get access to jobs that I am not approved by Xometry to take (Capability approval status)
I SHALL NOT get access to jobs if Im not allowed to receive work (Partner Status)
I SHALL NOT get access to jobs if my ability to complete that job has expired (Cabability Expiration Date)

As a non-engineer I SHALL have access to self-service analytics and traceability that help me understand the impact of the NEW Eligibility layer so that I can maintain trust in the system and be able to understand/explain how its working to other people without ad-hoc assistance from Engineering or Analytics.
I SHALL be able to understand the following about Jobs:

As a non-engineer user I SHALL be able to enter an Offer ID and see which Eligibility criteria did or did not trigger so that I can validate and understand the rules of the Eligibility Layer and how it interacts with a particular Job Offer without eng/analytics support.

As a non-engineer user I SHALL be able to enter an Offer ID and see a list of all partners that were determined to be eligible when it was run through the new Eligibility layer so that I can understand which partners would get access to that Job Offer without eng/analytics support.
I SHALL be able to understand the following about Partners

As a non-engineer I SHALL be able to enter a Partner ID and see which Eligibility Criteria did or did not trigger so that I can validate and understand the rules of the Eligibility Layer and how it interacts with each Partner without eng/analytics support.

As a non-engineer I SHALL be able to enter a Partner ID and timeframe criteria and see a list of all Job Offers that would be available to them when they were run through the new Eligibility Layer so that I can understand what Job Offers a partner would get access to without eng/analytics support.

As a non engineer I SHOULD have access to self-service analytics and traceability that helps me understand the impact of the current (legacy) Capable Partner API so that I can understand/explain how its working to other people without ad-hoc assistance from Engineering or Analytics
I SHOULD be able to understand the following about Jobs:

As a non-engineer user I SHOULD be able to enter an Offer ID and see which criteria in the Capable Partners API did or did not trigger so that I can validate and understand the rules of the Capable Partners API and how it interacts with a particular Job Offer without eng/analytics support.

As a non-engineer user I SHOULD be able to enter an Offer ID and see a list of all partners that were determined to be eligible when it was run through the Capable Partners API so that I can understand which partners would get access to that Job Offer without eng/analytics support.
I SHOULD be able to understand the following about Partners

As a non-engineer I SHOULD be able to enter a Partner ID and see which criteria in the Capable Partners API did or did not trigger so that I can understand the rules of the Capable Partners API and how it interacts with each Partner without eng/analytics support.

As a non-engineer I SHOULD be able to enter a Partner ID and timeframe criteria and see a list of all Job Offers that would be available to them when they were run through the new Capable Partners API so that I can understand what Job Offers a partner would get access to without eng/analytics support.

As a non-engineer I SHOULD have access to self-service analytics and traceability that helps me compare the output of the Eligibility layer vs the Capable Partners API so that I can understand the impact the Eligibility layer would make if we moved it to production.
I SHOULD be able to compare the average number of available job offers per partner between the Capable Partners API and the Eligibility Layer so that I can see the difference in output
I SHOULD be able to segment this by partner outsourcing group so that I can understand how each segment is impacted by the Eligibility layer
I SHOULD be able to segment this by job type process so that I can understand how each segment is impacted by the eligibility layer

I SHOULD be able to provide a timeframe criteria and compare the average number of available job offers per partner so that I can determine which eligibility layer constraints most limit job offer level coverage and prioritize rules for live experimentation
I SHOULD be able to segment this by partner outsourcing group so that I can understand how each segment is impacted by the Eligibility layer
I SHOULD be able to segment this by job type process so that I can understand how each segment is impacted by the eligibility layer

This is the next milestone in the 3 layer cake, and will be covered in this PRD:
With eligibility logic validated, future iterations may introduce the ability to manage, simulate and make changes to the eligibility layer (And future sourcing layers).

As a Business Owner I need to adjust an eligibility rule for a specific job offer or rule category and immediately see how partner eligibility changes so that I can safely expand coverage when appropriate.
As a Business Owner I need all eligibility rule changes to be versioned, auditable, and reversible so that governance and accountability are maintained.
Eligibility Planning and Simulation User Stories
As a Business Owner I need to simulate the impact of changing a single eligibility rule on partner coverage across job offers so that I can evaluate tradeoffs before making a live change.
As a Business Owner I need to see how a proposed eligibility rule change would affect partner coverage by process and outsourcing group so that I can avoid unintended supply distortions.
As a Business Owner I need to compare multiple eligibility scenarios side by side so that I can choose the option that maximizes coverage while preserving quality and compliance.

As a Business Owner I need to run a simulation that identifies partners who fail eligibility due to a small number of rules so that I can prioritize outreach and coaching to help them expand their eligibility and access more job offers.

Why do each of these fields seem necessary for the eligibility layer?
What is it: the material specified by the customer for the job

Why should it be in eligibility: material compatibility determines whether a partner can physically manufacture the part.  In additive, the process and material are inseparable, making this a capability required for eligibility
What is it: The manufacturing process required to produce the job
Why should it be in eligibility: If a partner is not approved for the required process, the job cannot be produced under any circumstance
CNC Machining, Sheet Cutting, Selective Laser Sintering (SLS)
The inspection requirements associated with the job.
Why should it be in eligibility:
Inspection requirements impose operational and compliance constraints that not all partners can meet.
Why should it be in eligibility:
Material certifications are legal or contractual requirements, and if a partner does not hold them, the job cannot be completed and is invalid by definition
Formal certifications held by the partner that are required for the job
Why should it be in eligibility:
Partner certifications are prerequisites for regulated or high risk work. Without the required certification, the partner cannot legally accept the job. This must be enforced upfront
The verified country or region where the partner produces parts
Why should it be in eligibility:
Some jobs have legal, regulatory, or customer imposed location constraints. If production location does not meet these requirements, the job cannot be fulfilled.

Note: A similar field titled 'Partner Exclusions and Sanctions' was proposed. To ensure accuracy, 'Location' should be mapped to Eligibility, while 'Sanctions' should be mapped to Target, as sanction statuses are subject to change.
An indicator that a capability has expired.
Why should it be in eligibility:
Expiration must be enforced to prevent invalid sourcing, but it does not need to exist as a product level eligibility rule
An indicator that a partners capability has been approved
Why should it be in eligibility:
Approval must be enforced, but it does not need to surface as a standalone eligibility field. It is an internal attribute of a capability
A trust and safety control indicating frozen exploded or restricted partners.
Why should it be in eligibility:
This is a safety and enforcement mechanism, not a capability decision. It belongs in the technical backend layer, not the hard eligibility rules.
